<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="19" type="differential diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="19">Differential diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="19">
Antenna orange ventrally, oval, longer than wide. Costal cell hyaline, bare basally. Alula bare medially. Pro- and mesofemur yellow. Metafemur orange on basal 1/5 and apical 3/5. Probasitarsomere, meso- and metabasitarsomere I-II yellow. Second tergum with a broad macula reaching apical 1/3. Third tergum with a broad macula, short in fourth. Sternite fourth to fifth black pilose. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Montoya" authorityYear="2020" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Argentinomyia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Argentinomyia puntarena" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="19" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="puntarena">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="19">Argentinomyia puntarena</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. nov. is similar in appearance to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Thompson" authorityYear="2020" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Argentinomyia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Argentinomyia talamanca" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="19" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="talamanca">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="19">Argentinomyia talamanca</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. nov., but in 
<taxonomicName genus="A." lsidName="A. talamanca" pageId="0" pageNumber="19" rank="species" species="talamanca">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="19">A. talamanca</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. nov. the antenna is brown; alula and costal cell are extensively microtrichose; femur is extensively brown; the second tergum has a pair of small maculae on basal 1/5 (see 'diagnostic 
<normalizedToken originalValue="features’">features'</normalizedToken>
under each species or key).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
