<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="19" type="comments">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="19">Comments.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="19">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Montoya" authorityYear="2020" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Argentinomyia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Argentinomyia puntarena" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="19" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="puntarena">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="19">Argentinomyia puntarena</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. nov. and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Thompson" authorityYear="2020" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Argentinomyia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Argentinomyia talamanca" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="19" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="talamanca">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="19">Argentinomyia talamanca</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. nov. can be confused or mistakenly identified as 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Curran" authorityYear="1930" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Xanthandrus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Xanthandrus mexicanus" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="19" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="mexicanus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="19">Xanthandrus mexicanus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Curran, 1930 due to the superficial similarity of these species. However, 
<taxonomicName genus="X." lsidName="X. mexicanus" pageId="0" pageNumber="19" rank="species" species="mexicanus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="19">X. mexicanus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be distinguished by the presence of the antennal cavity broadly confluent (synapomorphy for 
